Linux Log Analysis – SSH Authentication Investigation
Project Overview
This project demonstrates how Linux authentication logs can be analyzed to detect suspicious login activity and investigate potential brute-force attacks.
A Linux virtual machine was used to simulate failed SSH login attempts. System logs were then reviewed using command-line tools to identify authentication failures and analyze the activity recorded in the logs.
This investigation replicates a basic Security Operations Center (SOC) log analysis task commonly performed by cybersecurity analysts.
Lab Environment
Operating System: Linux VM (RHEL based)
Virtualization Platform: VirtualBox
Log File Analyzed: /var/log/secure
Service Investigated: SSH (Secure Shell)
Tools Used:
ssh
grep
wc
ss
systemctl
Step 1 – Verify SSH Service Status
First, the SSH service was verified to ensure it was running on the system.
Command used:
systemctl status sshd
This confirms that the OpenSSH service is active and listening for connections.
📸 Evidence
Step 2 – Verify SSH Port is Listening
Next, the system was checked to confirm that the SSH service was listening on port 22.
Command used:
ss -tulpn
This command displays all active listening ports and the associated processes.
📸 Evidence
Step 3 – Generate Failed SSH Login Attempts
To simulate suspicious activity, multiple failed login attempts were performed using invalid credentials.
Command used:
ssh fakeuser@localhost
The system rejected the login attempts because the username does not exist.
This activity generated authentication failure entries in the system logs.
📸 Evidence
Step 4 – Review Authentication Logs
Linux authentication activity is recorded in the following log file:
/var/log/secure
This file contains records of login attempts, authentication successes, and failures.
Command used:
sudo cat /var/log/secure
The log entries include:
timestamp
username attempted
authentication method
source IP address
failure reason
📸 Evidence
Step 5 – Filter Failed Login Attempts
To identify authentication failures, the grep command was used to filter log entries containing "Failed password".
Command used:
sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/secure
This command isolates only the failed login attempts from the authentication logs.
📸 Evidence
Step 6 – Count Failed Login Attempts
To determine the total number of failed login attempts, the following command was used:
sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/secure | wc -l
Result:
25 failed login attempts
This confirms that multiple authentication failures occurred during the simulation.
📸 Evidence
Log Analysis Findings
The investigation identified multiple failed SSH login attempts recorded in the authentication logs.
Each log entry contained:
timestamp of the attempt
username used in the login attempt
source IP address
SSH session details
authentication failure message
Example log entry:
Failed password for invalid user fakeuser from ::1 port 53918 ssh2
Repeated login failures such as these can indicate brute-force attacks against an SSH service.
Security Recommendations
If this activity occurred in a production environment, the following security controls should be implemented:
Block suspicious IP addresses using firewall rules
Implement Fail2Ban to automatically block repeated login attempts
Disable root login over SSH
Enforce SSH key-based authentication
Monitor authentication logs regularly
Implement intrusion detection systems
